<h1>To the President of Congress</h1>

<div class="docbody">

<p>Amsterdam, 10 July 1781. <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr> and signature in John Thaxters hand <span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Papers of the Continental Congress. Originals in the National Archives: Record Group 360. Microfilm edition in 204 reels. Usually cited in the present work from the microfilms, but according to the original series and volume numbering devised in the State Department in the early 19th century; for example, PCC, No. 93, III, i.e. the third volume of series 93.&lt;/expan&gt; ]">PCC</span>, No. 84, III, f. 268269. <span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">printed</span> : <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Francis Wharton, ed., &lt;i&gt;The Revolutionary Diplomatic Correspondence of the United States&lt;/i&gt;, Washington, 1889; 6 vols. ]">Wharton, ed., <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr. Amer. Rev.</span></span>, 4:556557.</p>
<p>John Thaxter wrote this letter during John Adams absence at Paris. It contains an English translation of an article that appeared in Dutch newspapers, including the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Gazette de Leyde</span> of 10 July. The article reported that on 4 July the Duke of Brunswick-Wolfenbttel informed the States General that he was grateful for the resolution of confidence it adopted on 2 July. He requested, however, an investigation of his conduct, which was the only means to absolve him fully from the charges made against him. The States General agreed to the investigation.</p>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="PJA11d366sn1">

